    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-07-02T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-07-02T13:00:00-05:00" n="706"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d706">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.04418/456a: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Chiefs of Certain American Diplomatic Missions</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="7" xml:id="d706fn7">In Belgium, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, and
                        Switzerland.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-07-02T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 2, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>As soon as you can conveniently assemble the opinion and reaction of important
                    officials and individuals to the vote in the House of Representatives Friday
                    night on the neutrality legislation<note n="8" xml:id="d706fn8">H. J. Res. 306
                        (introduced May 19) as passed by the House of Representatives June 30, 1939,
                        included the embargo clause as section 2; see <hi rend="italic"
                            >Congressional Record</hi>, vol. 84, pt. 8, p. 8514. It was referred to
                        the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations, July 5, 1939.</note> I would like
                    to have a report on the subject together with your own comment and appraisal of
                    the effects of the vote on the policy of the government to which you are
                    accredited and upon the European situation generally.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
